snippet.textDisplay: with regards to roof framing, don't cut a stack a roof (the process you described of someone building the roof), instead you order trusses which arrive on site on a crane truck and you have them hoist the truss packages up onto the tops of the walls, unpack them and "roll them" (stand them up in place) and nail them in place so its a modular mechanism and you can get scissor trusses to create vaulted ceilings in areas you want higher ceilings.
snippet.textOriginal: with regards to roof framing, don't cut a stack a roof (the process you described of someone building the roof), instead you order trusses which arrive on site on a crane truck and you have them hoist the truss packages up onto the tops of the walls, unpack them and "roll them" (stand them up in place) and nail them in place so its a modular mechanism and you can get scissor trusses to create vaulted ceilings in areas you want higher ceilings.

snippet.textDisplay: Man, I'd just go with one slightly larger window and leaving those drain pipes be. Also, I've worked with great carpenters who would build an entire house cutting on the ground instead of taking 5 minutes to knock together a sturdy table to work from for everything from cutting to nailing headers together etc. which makes the works so much more convenient and thus much faster. Sturdy saw horse bases and screw a single sheet of ply to a couple 2x4's on edge and toe screw them to the sawhorses and voila, you're done and you've got a proper workstation.
snippet.textOriginal: Man, I'd just go with one slightly larger window and leaving those drain pipes be.
